lO. non auspicatos : before leaving Rome to take over the com- mand of an army, the general offered sacrifice to Capitoline Jupiter, and took the auspices (auspicia) or omens. If these were favourable, he marched at once ; if not, he waited until they were so. This act is expressed by the verb auspicari, so that exercitus auspicatus means “ an army to which the omens are favourable ’² ; while non auspicatus or inauspicatae means “for which the omens have not been duly taken, or are unfavourable.'' Unfavourable omens were supposed to bode misfortune and the displeasure of the gods ; and conversely, if an army proved unfortunate, it was supposed that the general had not duly taken the auspices.

ll. adiecisse : the infinitive depends upon renidet, as if the latter were a verb of rejoicing. Properly renideo is “ to shine again,'’ “ to glisten.” It is used here of one who “ glows with pride ” that a thing has happened.

See Index, avo. DAcus, Ammopsx, for the allusions, which are important.
